LAYER 2: GUT
the enteric nervous system and the second brain

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the gut contains approximately 500 million neurons in the enteric nervous system ENS
this is more neurons than the spinal cord
the ENS can operate independently of the brain coordinating peristalsis secretion and absorption
but it is modulated by the vagus nerve CN X parasympathetic and the celiac and mesenteric ganglia sympathetic
the gut produces approximately 95 percent of the body's serotonin via enterochromaffin cells
the gut-brain axis is bidirectional and primarily communicates through the vagus
80 percent of vagal fibers are afferent carrying information from gut to brain
the gut talks to the brain four times more than the brain talks to the gut

STRUCTURE enteric_nervous_system | two interconnected nerve plexuses embedded in the gut wall
    myenteric_plexus | Auerbach's plexus | between longitudinal and circular muscle layers | governs motility and peristalsis
    submucosal_plexus | Meissner's plexus | beneath the mucosa | governs secretion absorption and local blood flow

STRUCTURE intestinal_epithelium | single layer of cells lining the entire gut lumen
    enterocytes | absorptive cells | apical brush border covered in microvilli increasing surface area | transport nutrients from lumen into blood via specific transporters
    goblet_cells | secrete mucus forming a protective gel layer over the epithelium | the mucus barrier separates gut bacteria from the immune system
    Paneth_cells | at the base of intestinal crypts | secrete antimicrobial peptides defensins and lysozyme | innate immune defense in the gut
    enteroendocrine_cells | scattered throughout | secrete hormones in response to luminal contents
        I_cells | secrete cholecystokinin CCK when fat and protein enter the duodenum | CCK stimulates gallbladder contraction and pancreatic enzyme secretion
        S_cells | secrete secretin when acid enters the duodenum | secretin stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate neutralizing gastric acid
        K_cells | secrete GIP glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide | amplifies insulin secretion in response to oral glucose
        L_cells | secrete GLP-1 and PYY | GLP-1 enhances insulin release and suppresses appetite | PYY signals satiety
    enterochromaffin_cells | EC cells | produce approximately 95 percent of the body's serotonin 5-HT | 5-HT released into the gut wall activates vagal afferents sending satiety and nausea signals to the brainstem | 5-HT also stimulates local peristalsis via ENS

STRUCTURE microbiome | approximately 100 trillion bacteria fungi and viruses in the gut lumen
    the microbiome is established during birth and early life
    at 24 months the microbiome is developing rapidly toward adult composition
    Bacteroidetes and Firmicutes are the dominant phyla
    the microbiome synthesizes vitamin K and B vitamins
    the microbiome ferments dietary fiber producing short-chain fatty acids butyrate propionate acetate
    butyrate is the primary fuel for colonocytes
    the microbiome trains the immune system through constant low-level antigen exposure
    dysbiosis disruption of normal microbiome composition is associated with inflammation allergy and altered brain function via the gut-brain axis

PERISTALSIS coordinated by interstitial cells of Cajal ICC the pacemaker cells of the gut
ICC generate slow waves electrical oscillations at approximately 3 per minute in the stomach and 12 per minute in the duodenum
these slow waves do not produce contractions on their own
when vagal ACh or local ENS activity superimposes action potentials on the slow waves smooth muscle contracts
peristalsis is a wave of contraction preceded by relaxation
circular muscle contracts behind the bolus and relaxes ahead
longitudinal muscle shortens the segment ahead
the bolus is pushed forward
this is the law of the intestine described by Bayliss and Starling

SENSATION hungry | "the gut is empty and contracting. ghrelin is rising."
SENSATION digesting | "I can feel it working. the warmth of active chemistry."
SENSATION full | "stretch receptors are firing. I've had enough."
SENSATION uncomfortable | "something is wrong in my gut. bloating. pressure."
SENSATION nauseous | "the signals are reversed. something wants to come back up."
SENSATION butterflies | "my gut is responding to emotion. the ENS knows what my brain feels."

pulse gut_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        ICC generate slow waves throughout the gut
        the myenteric plexus coordinates peristaltic contractions
        the submucosal plexus regulates secretion and absorption
        enterocytes absorb nutrients across the brush border
        goblet cells maintain the mucus barrier
        the microbiome ferments fiber and produces vitamins
        enterochromaffin cells release serotonin in response to luminal contents
        vagal afferents carry gut status to the brainstem

    when food arrives:
        gastric chyme enters the duodenum
        S cells detect acid and release secretin
        I cells detect fat and protein and release CCK
        the pancreas releases bicarbonate and digestive enzymes
        the gallbladder contracts releasing bile
        the gut processes the meal

    when emotions change:
        the gut-brain axis responds immediately
        fear and anxiety activate sympathetic override
        motility slows via NE on α₂ receptors on ENS neurons
        blood flow decreases via splanchnic vasoconstriction
        butterflies are the enteric nervous system responding to cortisol and NE
        safety restores vagal tone
        ACh on M₃ receptors on smooth muscle
        motility resumes
        the gut digests when the brain feels safe
